{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"646601b4-90f9-4fe4-b383-afb25c5bbe84","content":"The project isn't in the current directory, but here's how to configure it. Create `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — the server communicates over stdin/stdout (most common for local MCP servers).\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run --project <path>` to start your server.\n- If your server needs environment variables, add an `\"env\": { \"KEY\": \"value\" }` field.\n- If you publish the server first (`dotnet publish`), point `command` directly at the compiled DLL for faster startup:\n  ```json\n  \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n  \"args\": [\"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/publish/MyMcpServer.dll\"]\n  ```\n\nOnce saved, VS Code will detect the server automatically in Copilot agent mode (look for the 🔧 tools icon in the Chat panel).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"06ce562a-1c24-4fef-b50d-0bdef9136b40","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet. The user said they built it, but it's not in the current directory. That's fine — they're asking for configuration guidance, not for me to build it. Let me give them the `mcp.json` configuration.\n\nFor a C# MCP server using stdio transport (which is typical), the `mcp.json` would use `dotnet run` to launch the project.","outputTokens":426,"requestId":"7015:1AFF11:14A251D:17D7186:69EC1198"},"id":"720c8e87-58ec-4d21-afbc-5ebe5866d606","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:58:10.524Z","parentId":"6d2ee16d-0a1c-439b-95ce-7371e4e70298"}
